‘Powys Fadog’ and ‘Powys Wenwynwyn’ -- tAppendix IV. The date of composition of Breuddwyd Rhonabwy -- tSelect bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst full-scale account of the medieval realm of Powys.Powys, extending over north-east and central Wales, was one of three great medieval Welsh polities, along with Gwynedd to the north and Deheubarth (south-west), occupying nearly a quarter of the country. However, it has been somewhat neglected by historians, who have tended to dismiss it as a satellite realm of England, and viewed its leaders as obstacles to the efforts of Gwynedd leaders to construct a principality of Wales. This book provides the first full, authoritative history of Powys in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries. It argues in particular that the Powysian rulers were dogged and resourceful survivors in the face of pressure from Welsh rivals and the problems ofinternal fragmentation; and that, paradoxically, co-operation with the English and intermarriage with marcher families underlay a desire to regain lands to the east lost in earlier centuries. Dr David Stephenson is anHonorary Research Fellow in the School of History, Welsh History and Archaeology, Bangor University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPowys (Wales)--History--To 1500. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBritish politics.  aarchaeology.  ahistorians.  ahistorical reference.  ahistory of Welsh politics.  ainternational relations.  amedieval Wales.  amedieval Welsh politics.  amedieval studies.  apolitical science history of Wales.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204856540uhttps://www.degruyt